<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>CBI EVIDENCE TO THE JOINT COMMITTEE ON THE DRAFT DEREGULATION BILL</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CBI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">– Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBI welcomes the opportunity to provide written evidence to the Joint Committee on the Draft Deregulation Bill. The CBI is the </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK’s leading business organisation, speaking for some 240,000 businesses that together employ around a third of the private sector workforce.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is a broad Bill which cuts across a number of policy areas and will affect certain sectors very specifically. Our evidence will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">address</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a number of the clauses which are most relevant to the business community as a whole. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over the past year there has been some positive news on the UK economy and for this nascent recovery to strengthen, so the UK achieves long-term, sustainable economic growth, public policy must be focused on creating the right conditions for growth, by supporting the private sector to drive the recovery. This Bill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should help support the government’s growth agenda</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by combining re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">peal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">form</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">usiness supports the overall intent behind the Bill: that the regulatory process should be one of amending, improving and scrapping of legislation where necessary.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In addition the Bill is a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> vehicle for significant and very positive reform</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, by setting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in place the framework for a more flexible, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">effective apprenticeship system. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Turning to the specific clauses:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Clause 2: Removal of employment tribunals’ power to make wider recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In an employment law framework based on individual rights, as in the UK, an independent arbitration system has a vital role to play. Employment tribunals rightly shape business behaviours through their rulings, however they are not best qualified to make company specific recommendations. For this reason the CBI called for the removal of employment tribunals’ power to make wider recommendations in our response to the Government Equalities Office consultation on the removal of enforcement measures from the Equality Act 2010</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support the inclusion of this measure in the Bill. For recommendations to be meaningful, the individual making them needs to have considerable understanding of the company, something which tribunals cannot gain through arbitrating a hearing. Indeed, badly crafted recommendations have the potential to be harmful, either through prescribing the wrong action or through legitimising wider behaviours not covered in the tribunals’ proposals. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Clause 3: English apprenticeships: simplification                                                                                </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To meet the UK’s future skills needs our education and skills system must be able to raise people to higher skills levels, address the shortages which employers identify and be tailored to best equip people for work</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. To achieve this, the CBI supports a new, simplified framework for apprenticeships which is focused on training outcomes for businesses. The proposals put forward by Doug Richard in his review, which are reflected in the Bill, were supported by the CBI</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Stripping back on the detailed prescription on content in the previous Act and allowing employers, and their representatives, to make representations on the standards for apprenticeships, are positive steps towards creating a more flexible system which will better meet the needs of both employers and apprentices. Similarly, providing further clarity about the employment status of apprentices will help all firms, but in particularly businesses navigating the system for first time and smaller firms. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These reforms rightly address problems within the existing apprenticeships framework. Given the devolved nature of education and skills policy, business understands that these reforms will only take effect within England and recognise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> them as a welcome step forward. At this stage business is comfortable about the level of detail within the Bill, so long as the on-going piloting and consultation process is completed, and changes are properly phased which can be dealt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as the secondary legislation adds further substance. Similarly, given the powers that the Bill allows to the Secretary of State business would seek clarity that any changes would be made in a timely and considered fashion. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Clauses 9, 10, 11 : Companies and insolvency </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The effectiveness of the audit market is being comprehensively addressed through two concurrent processes: an EU audit market reform package consisting of a Directive and a Regulation; and a Competition Commission review into the UK audit market which recently reported its final conclusions. The CBI encourages the government to ensure that proposed changes in this Bill are made in light of developments in both sets of on-going reforms.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Both initiatives are expected to conclude in 201</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4 and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ssues of auditor appointment and rotation are among the many aspects of the audit market being dealt with in these reviews.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Clause 22: Removal of restrictions on provision of passenger rail services</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The franchise system has delivered huge investment in our rail network and better outcomes for passengers. This clause, which will allow for decentralising of rail franchises and give local authorities similar powers on to franchising to that of the GLA, is in line with the findings of the Brown Review on franchising. The experience of Transport For London shows that the devolution of franchises can, and has the potential to, deliver positive outcomes for relevant authorities.  We need a rail network fit for the 21st century and that is why the CBI welcomes devolution as a positive change to the franchise system.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Clause 31: Abolition of office of Chief Executive of Skills Funding </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The apprenticeship funding is system is complex and poorly understood by employers – one of our key policy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">priorities in this area </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is a simplified system. The abolition of this role is a practical measure which will help achieve a simpler relationship between the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Skills Funding A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gency and BIS – an aim which CBI fully supports.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:2.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Clause 32: Further and higher education sectors: reduction of burdens </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Reforms which allow further education colleges to be more flexible and responsive to employer needs should deliver better outcomes for the individuals studying, as well as the businesses seeking highly skilled, well-equipped employees. Alongside this flexibility, business needs assurance that further education staff are capable of providing high quality teaching and training. This will be provided by the new Education and Training Foundation which has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">established to give colleges greater support and guidance on developing their staff. This reform will extend to further education colleges the trust instilled in universities to appoint staff, without detailed requirements set out in statute.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Clause 33: Schools: reduction of burdens</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Reducing the burden on schools – and delegating and devolving powers to governing bodies and to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">teacher</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s – is absolutely the right approach and one that business supports.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> And the measures set out at Clause 33 and in Schedule 14 are a part of this.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It will b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e important, however, that g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overnment ensure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the right safeguards are in place to ensure that schools are properly supported in the new educational landscape.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This must include championing the importance of good governance and effective governing bodies and promoting the continuous professional development of school leaders</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Clause 58: Exercise of regulatory functions: economic growth</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Business believes that regulation has an important role within the economy: providing a framework for markets to work, setting standards and providing protections to individuals and consumers. Regulation, enforcement and regulators’ engagement with industry impacts business behaviour and therefore wider economic conditions. It is for these reasons business welcomed the proposal that non-economic regulators </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have a duty to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regard the impact of their actions on economic growth. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A regulator’s primary duty of protection is not incompatible with the aim of supporting economic growth and it is important to state that giving regulators a complementary economic duty should not undermine their primary duty. Rather it would ensure that regulators strike a balance between these two with the aim of preventing sub-optimal regulatory decisions or practices that hamper economic growth. For some regulators this is already taken </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">account in their existing practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, in other cases this should provide an impetus for regulators to view themselves as within – not outside of – the UK economy. Therefore, the CBI supports a principles-based, statutory duty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> non-economic regulators being introduced in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Bill. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In order for a new duty to be effective its objective must be clear.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In the present drafting there appears to be two objectives of the duty: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regard to the desirability of promoting economic growth and, underpinning that, exercis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> regulatory functions in a proportionate manner. The latter is a principle of good regulation which all regulators should adhere to – which does, indirectly, aid the better functioning of the economy – while an explicit ‘growth duty’ should ensure that a regulators’ behaviour supports the sustainable, long-term growth of the UK economy. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Enshrining both of these duties in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a welcome step. But while they are interconnected – good regulatory practice underpins economic growth – it would be clearer if they were separated and the application of both duties targeted accordingly. For ex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ample, a better regulation duty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> promoting proportionality could be applied to all regulators, while a duty to support UK economic growth could be targeted towards regulators where this would be most meaningful and have the greatest economic impact. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBI’s submission to the Better Regulation Delivery Office </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consultation on the duty to have regard to growth </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">highlighted the blurring of these two concepts in the original proposal and recommended a clearer wording and targeting for the ‘growth duty’ element</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The growth duty n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eeds to provide regulators with the legal certainty to underpin their actions and the flexibility to apply it according to their specific regulatory duties. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It could therefore help if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the wording of a growth duty could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, for example,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> require regulators </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘to support and encourage the sustainable development of the United Kingdom economy in general’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To be meaningful businesses believe that an explicit growth duty should be applied where it can provide the greatest support to private-sector growth. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CBI members therefore believe that some differentiation between regulators would be helpful in applying the growth duty. The purpose of differentiation is simply to recognise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> regulatory functions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the non-economic regulators</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> vary significantly and that, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s a result, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ir </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">application of a growth duty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and its impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will differ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">18.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Given the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ari</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation amongst </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the non-economic regulators, the CBI has proposed that the applicability of a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> growth duty c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ould be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> targeted on the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> individual</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> regulator,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> according to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regulator’s proximity to market</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and economic impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The purpose of such an approach is to ensure that a growth duty is carefully defined, targeted and supported by guidance for the regulators who can deploy it effectively. Otherwise the growth duty would be undermined. For example, where businesses do not see it as relevant or meaningful for those who regulate them or if it created extra regulatory burden without having any tangible economic impact, the concept of a growth duty would be weakened. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">19.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">egulators</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, whose decisions and practices </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can impact on competitive behaviour in a sector or the economy as a whole, wider economic stability or on the attractiveness of the UK as a place to invest are those for whom a growth duty is the most relevant. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These bodies operate very close to the market and their economic impact is very clear: the growth duty is therefore an important and meaningful concept for them. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Pensions Regulator (tPR) and the Groceries Code Adjudicator exemplify some of those bodies that have a very direct impact on the economy</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">20.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For regulators who </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may be balancing preservation, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">individual or environmental </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">protection, planning, or sustainability issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">business </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">believe a growth duty should apply and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would welcome recognition and understanding that decisions have taken account of what will support and encourage the sustainable development of the UK economy. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, because these bodies operate at a slight distance from the market – their economic impact is more indirect – it is worth recognising that the impact of a growth duty will differ for this type of organisations. This could be reflected in the wording of the duty or simply in the supporting guidance and communication. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">21.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CBI members feel that there will be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">certain regulators for whom a growth duty </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is unlikely to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be relevant or helpful. While recognising that all regulators, through their policies, regulations and enforcement behaviours have some degree of influence on the UK economy, there is a point at which the regulator’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">behaviour is so far removed from the market and wider UK economy that a growth duty would lack meaning. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">odies such as Ofqual, the Office for Fair Access and the Care Quality Co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mmission would fall into this category</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">22.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Finally, there will need to be clear communication to regulators and the regulated entities about new duties. Currently, there is some ambiguity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> amongst businesses and policymakers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> about the impact and application of the growth duty. The scrutiny of the Bill in this pre-legislative phase and during the parliamentary process will help to clarify this, as will supporting guidance in due course.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CBI</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Annex I – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">CBI response</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">The Future of Apprenticeships in England: Next Steps from the Richard Review</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBI is the UK’s leading business organisation, speaking for some 240,000 businesses that together employ around a third of the private sector workforce. With offices across the UK as well as representation in Brussels, Washington, Beijing and Delhi the CBI communicates the British business voice around the world.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBI welcomes the opportunity to respond to the Department for Education (DfE) and Department for Business Innovation and Skills (BIS) joint consultation on reforming apprenticeships in England. A core element of the UK’s long-term growth strategy is raising levels of workforce skills so that businesses are equipped with the talent they need to succeed. Doug Richard was right to highlight in his review that apprenticeships are essential for delivering the necessary skills to meet the changing needs of our economy. Businesses value the practical, work-focussed nature of apprenticeship programmes and the CBI welcomes the government’s stated aim of ensuring that all apprenticeships are rigorous and responsive to employers’ needs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The reforms proposed in this consultation offer an opportunity to shift the focus of the apprenticeship system towards outcomes and quality. To do this, business must genuinely be in the driving seat, setting industry standards and making decisions about provision. Business has the appetite for such a fundamental change, but it must be underpinned by mechanisms to harness business input into the design and delivery of training, a shakeup of the way that funding and incentives flow through the system and avoiding unnecessary bureaucracy. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In this submission we argue that:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To underpin a truly demand-led system, businesses and ministers need to devise a much simpler funding system that will empower employers to bring in high-quality provision that is relevant and directly addresses the needs of their business</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Businesses should be trusted to set the expected standards that underpin the apprenticeship programme</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Businesses have the appetite for greater involvement in the apprenticeships system, but we need structures at the national and local level to harness employer engagement </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improving trust and confidence in apprenticeships requires high standards of inspection and rigorous assessment, but government should avoid proxies for quality, unless driven by demand from businesses</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The road to apprenticeships should not just start at 16. As part of a more coherent system, business wants improved careers advice and clear routes into technical education from 14, alongside tougher, new gold standard vocational “A-levels” at 18.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">To underpin a truly demand-led system, businesses and ministers need to devise a much simpler funding system that will empower employers to bring in high-quality provision that is relevant and directly addresses the needs of their business</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Business leadership on apprenticeships must be underpinned by a shakeup of system incentives. For too long, the system has encouraged provision based around what the government is prepared to fund rather than what businesses need. The ramifications of this on business growth are clear, where growing firms are struggling to recruit skilled staff without hollowing out their supply chains. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Employers have been pushing for a more demand-led system for a decade or more, but to date government reforms have neither moved quickly enough nor represented the fundamental shift required. The funding reforms proposed by Doug Richard represent a real opportunity to drive a demand-led system and we are encouraged by the government’s appetite for change. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On first analysis, the CBI believes that the tax credit model represents the most effective way of delivering a truly demand-led funding system for apprenticeships. Key advantages of using the tax system include its potential simplicity, by aligning with existing processes for employers, and existing monitoring and accountability mechanisms. A smooth transition that preserves capacity is essential, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but through systematic and careful piloting we believe this can be delivered. The prize of a truly demand-led system that works for business of all sizes would be substantial. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Alongside a reform of apprenticeship funding, business has identified the need to seed fund clusters of skills provision – local, sectorally and down supply chains. A centrally held fund, like the Employer Ownership Pilots, that can be bid for by different consortia who can make a strong business case is preferable to directing public funding to Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) (as recommended in the Heseltine Review). Local co-ordination should focus on ensuring that LEPs and businesses are working together to map and identify skills needs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Businesses should be trusted to set the expected standards that underpin the apprenticeship programme</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A core element of the UK’s long-term growth strategy is equipping businesses with the talent they need to succeed. It is therefore welcome that the government recognises that apprenticeships are essential for raising skill levels across the economy and for supporting people into good careers. The economic returns from the apprenticeship programme are already significant</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but it is right that we should be more ambitious about the social and economic value that the programme can deliver. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Evidence suggests that we need a much closer alignment between the outputs of the system and the needs of industry. This was a welcome conclusion of the Richard Review, but also evident in the findings of the National Audit Office (NAO)</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the Lord Heseltine Review of Growth</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Moreover, this point is underlined by empirical data on the UK’s skills system, for example: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Commission for Employment and Skills (UKCES) estimates that 16% of all vacancies across the economy are due to skill shortages, rising to a 24% in manufacturing and 19% in construction</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Centre for Economic and Social Exclusion (CESI) data shows that in crucial sectors, skills supply is mismatched to demand. For every skills achievement in building services engineering, 1.8 vacancies are created, rising to 2.2 in construction and 2.4 in automotive. Conversely in sectors like hair and beauty only 0.2 vacancies exist for every skills achievement in that sector</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is an urgent need to refocus the system so that it responds effectively to the demands of business. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Business agrees with Doug Richard that apprenticeships should be redefined to focus on where they can add most value. We broadly agree with the proposed criteria for apprenticeships, particularly that they should be stretching, reflect real job roles and be deliverable by smaller employers. Introduction of standards along these lines, alongside the stripping out of red tape, can help raise the status of vocational education. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The vast majority of businesses involved in delivering apprenticeships have an interest in ensuring that programmes deliver the substantial new skills that will bring the strongest boosts to business productivity (see exhibit 1 for examples). The approach to ensuring this in every case should be light touch: one way to do this might be via short, high level, business-led statements describing what capabilities an apprentice should have at the end of their studies. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Exhibit 1: Employers are invested in apprenticeships that deliver substantial new skills</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“As a company, serving an industry that relies on having a skilled, competent and qualified workforce to deliver its business objectives, a successful apprenticeship scheme has been and continues to be a key focus of our strategy. [Company name] takes its investment in its people very seriously with the engineering academy being just one part of our learning and development offering, with our leadership academy forming the other part”.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">HR Director, Engineering Firm</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“People are an absolute priority for [company name] and fundamental to our success. Central to our vision and aspirations is our policy of providing career opportunities that allow all employees to develop to their full potential. [Company name] invests over £30million annually in training our employees as they must be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">expertly skilled to fulfil the high expectations of our customers. For their hard work and achievements our employees deserve to be recognised beyond our company.” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Education Manager, Retailer</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Feedback from CBI members suggests that there is a need to clarify how traineeships will fit with the recommendation for a redefinition of Level 2 apprenticeships in the Richard Review. Apprenticeships at level 2 should be preserved where they are a vital part of a company’s training offer, with a subsequent route to level 3 available. Other level 2 training might be offered effectively through traineeships or another framework.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBI is concerned about the potential conflict between requiring an apprenticeship to deliver skills that reflect real job roles on the one hand, and transferable skills on the other. To avoid apprenticeships that are too general, we recommend a model based around a combination of core and deep-seated subject knowledge, allowing qualifications to be relevant across a sector while containing a portion of employer-specific content. Every framework should also seek to foster the development of behaviours and attitudes that are essential to success in work and life.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBI is concerned by a uniform move to one standard per occupation and one qualification per standard. The government is right to worry about complexity, but the answer to this lies in ensuring that every qualification has business backing, not a forced move to single qualifications. Ultimately, industry should decide on the appropriate number of qualifications and standards required to match the capabilities and outcomes required of the wider sector. To assist with a smooth transition to the new system, the CBI recommends an interim review of existing frameworks taking into account the Richard Review recommendations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CBI members have emphasised that off-site learning is already a substantial part of most apprenticeships and the government should not make it a mandatory criterion of apprenticeships. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Businesses have the appetite for greater involvement in the apprenticeships system, but we need structures at the national and local level to harness employer involvement</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The proposed reforms amount to a seismic change for the way that businesses interact with the apprenticeship system, from leading the design of frameworks to engagement in delivery and setting effective assessment. CBI members show a strong appetite to play this leadership role, as demonstrated at the CBI/BIS roundtable attended by Dr Mike Keoghan in April 2013. This willingness is further evident in the number and ambition of bids to the UKCES Employer Ownership Pilots. Successful bids have seen employers collaborate to design bold and innovative skills solutions (see Exhibit 2 for examples). Conversations with members suggest an increase in the ambition and number of bids to the second round, particularly in the creation of industrial partnerships.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Exhibit 2: The UKCES Employer Ownership of Skills Pilots</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Nissan</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The north east based car manufacturer is set to need 2,000 new staff to meet production demands over the next two years, a huge challenge given regional skills shortages and a need to boost skills levels in a supply chain that provides around 80% of its components. Their winning EOP bid will see Nissan develop four new training programmes to boost skills at all levels of the organisation from existing workers to new recruits and across their supply chain.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Siemens </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The successful bid of CBI member Siemens will see them work with organisations including sector skills council Semta to extend its re-employment and apprenticeship programmes to its key suppliers – a great example of how innovative skills provision can support a sector</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Harnessing business engagement will require effective mechanisms and support at the national and local level to ensure that employers of all sizes can engage with the system, particularly SMEs. Feedback from CBI members shows strong support for collaborative, rather than competitive, mechanisms based around the consolidation of training budgets and building clusters that cut across sectors, local areas and supply chains. Funding reform can help businesses to cooperate at the local level in a way that makes sense to them – that might be the local chamber of commerce, LEPs, or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regional body (like the proposal for Skills NE</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">). Such groups will engage small firms more effectively. One way to do this is through the Employer Ownership Pilots, which focus on the growth of sustainable, business led, local links that involve SMEs and supply chains for the benefit of the wider economy. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Existing mechanisms that already result in genuine business engagement should be maintained. There are examples of Sector Skills Councils (SSCs) that are well regarded and meaningfully involve business in training design. The government must work with industry to ensure that the appropriate level of business representation is being achieved. One way to introduce greater flexibility would be to open up the Employer Investment Funding beyond SSCs to enable groups of employers or other intermediary bodies to deliver skills solutions for wider sectors. CBI members have highlighted that in some circumstances, the SSC body can be too big or generalising to be useful – opening up the fund could allow new entrants to form smaller, more responsive representative bodies. We would be concerned about the potential loss of provision where SSCs are currently well regarded and have genuine and meaningful engagement with business on training design. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CBI members consistently highlight the overly-bureaucratic nature of the skills system as being a major disincentive for engagement, particularly for smaller employers. We welcome progress towards stripping back apprenticeship red tape and helping SMEs to become more engaged. We are looking to the government to bring the experience and knowledge of these conversations to play when planning the new apprenticeships in detail. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Improving trust and confidence requires high standards of inspection and rigorous assessment, but the government should avoid proxies for quality unless driven by demand from businesses</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBI agrees with Doug Richard that apprenticeships should be about quality, not just high numbers. Business broadly agrees with the government proposals to build on existing arrangements to ensure that inspection arrangements are an assurance of quality. Improving the approval process for providers is vital, particularly in situations where local competition is limited.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CBI agrees that plans for rigorous end stage assessment could help ensure the trust of businesses, young people and their parents in the quality of the apprenticeship programme. Businesses agree that an apprentice should be able to demonstrate the breadth of their competency at the end of an apprenticeship and this assessment should take the form of a practical assessment, designed by industry and taking place over a period of time, as deemed appropriate by the business. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Feedback from business suggests there is support in some sectors and geographic areas for adopting kite marking. Kite marking may have a role to play in some schemes, but the government is right to say that it should be voluntary and led by demand from business. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Businesses believe that grading of apprenticeships is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not necessary – providing there is rigorous assessment, apprenticeship completion should mean that the individual has the competencies set out in the original standard. The government should consider working within existing structures to motivate individuals, for example ensuring routes to progression onto higher level apprenticeships. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The road to apprenticeships should not just start at 16. As part of a more coherent system, business wants improved careers advice and clear routes into technical education from 14, alongside tougher, new gold standard vocational “A-levels” at 18</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The road to apprenticeships does not simply start at 16 – students’ inspiration, aptitudes and attitudes must be inbuilt from much earlier. The CBI’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">First steps</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> report in 2012 set out business priorities for a radical overhaul of the system from nursery onwards in support of this aim</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Combined with raising the participation age, on-going reform of qualifications at 16 and 18 necessitates a more holistic approach to the pathways that young people take from 14 onwards. This requires the reform of GCSEs, A-Levels and vocational qualifications that are already underway, but it must be set in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a context of preparation for the outcomes we want for every young person. A review of the pathways available to all young people from age 14 should make available vocational A-levels for technical and applied subjects to avoid the confusing mass of different offers that are currently available. Such a change also introduces scope for some students to focus on a technical education earlier, combined with a tailored core skills curriculum, from the age of 14 by moving on to institutions such as the growing number of university technical colleges. It would also allow higher apprenticeships, which offer entry at 16, to be fully aligned with the school system. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that every young person should expect an individual learning plan for their path to 18, which they develop working with the school and other key sources of advice, like their parents, business visitors to the school and careers advisers. Such an approach would go further towards encouraging the take up of the most economically valuable qualifications than the current review of criteria for inclusion in league tables can go alone. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clear routes into vocational education must be combined with effective careers inspiration, advice and guidance. Provision currently is not up to the mark – the latest CBI/Pearson Education and Skills Survey</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> found that almost three quarters of respondents (72%) reporting that advice is not good enough. The government has made some changes in this area, with the new duty on schools to provide advice and the opening of the National Careers Service, which focuses on older people. But real change will only come with a comprehensive new approach that engages businesses. The focus of careers guidance must shift from being about information towards helping young people to navigate the masses of information available, but in a way that leaves them inspired and on a practical path to achieve their goals. The CBI believes that this should be the goal of a fully operational National Careers Service.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CBI Education &amp; Skills</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">May 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> CBI response to the GEO consultation on removal of enforcement measures from the Equality Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> 2010</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Tomorrow’s Growth,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> CBI July 2013 </span><a href="http://www.cbi.org.uk/campaigns/skills-for-growth/tomorrows-growth-report/tomorrows-growth-report-page-turner/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.cbi.org.uk/campaigns/skills-for-growth/tomorrows-growth-report/tomorrows-growth-report-page-turner/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> CBI response to the DfE/BIS consultation ‘The future of apprenticeships in England: next steps from the Richard Review’, May 2013. Included as an annex </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">CBI response to Better Regulation Delivery Office consultation on non-economic regulators: duty to have regard to growth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">, May 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> The CBI pushed strongly for tPR to have a new statutory objective relating to growth, a commitment to which is being taken forward in the Pensions Bill.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> The average Apprenticeship completer increases  business productivity by £214 per week, according to CEBR</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> NAO, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; fon